<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / International Company News: Ciba ready to forge US alliances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ciba, the largest of the big three Swiss drugs companies, said yesterday it
would soon sign alliances in the US in response to the changing healthcare
environment there.
Mr Pierre Douaze, head of Ciba's pharmaceuticals division, said deals could
be done with other drugs companies or with organisations closer to the
patient, such as drug distributors and health management organisations.
The move would be partly in response to the Dollars 6bn acquisition last
year by Merck, the biggest US drugs company, of Medco, a drug distributor.
That deal was a response to efforts by government and employers to cut
healthcare spending by insisting on discounts and buying from groups of
companies.
Mr Douaze said Ciba was looking at several options and that a decision would
be made soon. 'We have to move before all the positions are taken,' he said.
Mr Douaze was speaking at the company's annual results presentation, which
revealed 1993 post-tax profits up 11.2 per cent to SFr1.78bn (Dollars
1.3bn), compared with figures for 1992 which were restated last summer to
conform with international accounting standards.
Sales rose to SFr22.65bn, a gain of 2 per cent in constant currency terms.
Earnings per share rose to SFr63.8 from SFr56 and the dividend is to be
lifted by SFr1 to SFr15 per share.
The company has three divisions: healthcare, industry and agriculture. Last
year saw healthcare overtake industry to become the companies biggest single
division with sales of SFr9.22bn, a rise of 5 per cent on 1992. Much of the
gain was the result of a 20 per cent sales increase at Ciba Vision thanks to
the popularity of contact lenses.
Sales at the industry division, which includes textile dyes, chemicals and
plastics, fell 1 per cent to SFr8.61bn. The decline was mostly accounted for
by a 21 per cent fall in sales of composite materials to the aerospace
industry, hit by defence cuts.
Agriculture sales rose 1 per cent to SFr4.8bn, in spite of pressure on the
business in Europe, where the Community Agricultural Policy has cut the
acreage of land under cultivation. Ciba said the European agricultural
products market was unlikely to grow for the next two to three years, but
growth would come from Asia and South America.
Last year, Ciba switched to guidelines of the International Accounting
Standards Committee (Iasc) and revised 1992 group net profit to SFr1.6bn
from SFr1.52bn.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
