<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Lower interest charges fuel Adwest's 21%
rise to Pounds 3.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Adwest, the automotive components and power systems group, yesterday
announced a 21 per cent jump in interim pre-tax profits fuelled by sharply
lower interest charges and a 20 per cent improvement in property.
Pre-tax profits for the six months to December 31 rose from Pounds 3.24m to
Pounds 3.93m, on flat sales of Pounds 63m. At the operating level profits
fell by 4 per cent to Pounds 4.04m.
Mr Fred Grant, who was making his last presentation as chairman and chief
executive before retiring in April, said he was confident Adwest would
progress this year.
'We take a fairly confident view of the future,' he said. For this reason
the interm dividend was increased by 5 per cent to 2.1p. Earnings rose by 9
per cent to 3.8p. Mr Grant said the group intended to hold dividend cover at
about this level.
The proceeds of the Pounds 22m rights issue in September, lower interest
rates and cash generation helped to cut debt charges from Pounds 1.28m to
Pounds 531,000. The property division increased its contribution from Pounds
1.33m to Pounds 1.59m.
Mr Graham Menzies, the chief executive-elect, said profits from the
manufacturing divisions had held up well when compared with last year's
exceptionally strong first half.
Profits had been hit by redundancy costs of Pounds 150,000 and bad debts of
about Pounds 100,000. Adwest had also suffered abortive acquisition costs
which had depressed profits.
The automotive division suffered from the French recession, with operating
profits 11 per cent lower at Pounds 1.44m, on sales 5 per cent down at
Pounds 36.87m. France continued to be difficult, although there were
tentative signs of an improvement.
Mr Menzies said recent increases in volumes from most of Adwest's main
customers had left order books about 12 per cent ahead in the automotive
division.
Power systems, which relies on defence related orders for about 48 per cent
of its business, had been increasingly competitive and margins had suffered.
Operating profits fell by 21 per cent to Pounds 1m, on sales 8 per cent
ahead to Pounds 24.54m. Mr Menzies said that while orders were still lower
than last year, there was some evidence that the decline had halted.
</TEXT>
