<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / BAe shows Pounds 2.9bn leasing exposure
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace disclosed yesterday that it has aircraft leasing
obligations of Pounds 2.9bn, compared with income that it expects to receive
on sub-leases to airlines of Pounds 1.8bn.
Mr Richard Lapthorne, finance director, said that losses on these leases and
the costs of restructuring the aviation business brought BAe near to
collapse over the past couple of years. 'We got very close,' he said.
Only an undisclosed part of sub-lease income is contractually committed,
though the group believes its estimate of what it will receive is prudent.
At the end of last year, provisions to cover the risk of leasing losses
stood at Pounds 653m.
BAe sold aircraft to banks and leased them back under agreements lasting
between 15 and 20 years, depending on aircraft type. It then rented them on
sub-leases of between three and five years to airlines.
Losses are made by BAe if sub-leases are not renewed. Mr Lapthorne said
that, in the past, BAe booked profits on these sales to banks and made only
small provisions to cover the risk of these losses. 'We have over-reported
profits in the past,' he said.
Mr Terry Smith, analyst at brokers Collins Stewart, said: 'These leasing
liabilities are extraordinary. We thought BAe was selling the planes to
airlines rather than renting them out on a short term basis.'
In the past three years, BAe's commercial aircraft division has lost Pounds
1.79bn in aggregate, including exceptional reorganisation costs and
provisions against losses on the leases, but excluding tax and interest
payments.
Counting the true cost, Page 27
</TEXT>
