<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Post Office urges stock market sale of minority shareholding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The management of the Post Office is pressing for a stock market flotation
through the public offer of a minority shareholding in an attempt to
dissuade the government from shelving privatisation as politically
unacceptable.
The suggested scheme - the sale of a 30-40 per cent stake - is known as the
'BP option', so-called because British Petrolem was government-controlled
but publicly quoted for most of this century before being sold off in the
late 1980s. Under Treasury rules, it was allowed to act as a private company
throughout.
Using this model, it is argued, would maintain the government's
responsibility for the Post Office's operations, reassuring the public about
the level of service. It would also give the Post Office the freedom to
borrow without adding to the government's budget deficit.
Privatisation is opposed by a number of backbench Tory MPs, who are worried
about the possible closure of village post offices and the withdrawal of
postal services to remote areas.
In an effort to placate them, the scheme proposes legislation stating that
before selling any further shares in the Post Office, the government would
have to seek permission from parliament.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, has said he believes
there is a strong economic case for privatisation. He is thought to favour
the sale of the Royal Mail together with the lossmaking Parcelforce, while
leaving the more politically sensitive Post Office Counters within the
public sector. However, the Post Office fears that the whole project may be
abandoned as too politically sensitive.
While the Post Office continues to press for commercial freedom, it claims
to have no preference for how it is obtained. Mr Bill Cockburn, managing
director, said: 'It doesn't really matter which route is taken, provided
it's a means to an end. If the government decides to separate the
businesses, the Post Office will work with the government to make that
successful.'
This would be equally true if the BP option were applied to the Royal Mail
alone, he said. 'The worst option is for the government to do nothing.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
