<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / The Lex Column: Italy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Italy's financial markets wanted a clear outcome to the general elections.
They have not really got one. Forming a government promises to be a much
harder task for the rightwing Freedom Alliance than winning the election,
and the markets have some grounds for anxiety about how its policies will
turn out.
The stock market might relish the continuation of the privatisation
programme: some juicy offerings are coming up in the insurance and energy
sector. But it is hard to square the Alliance's commitment to lower taxes
with continuing reduction of the budget deficit. If that approach did not
work in Reagan's America, it is unlikely to in Berlusconi's Italy.
Arguably both equities and bonds are cheap. With inflation heading below 4
per cent this year, long-term yields of over 9 per cent provide a
substantial real return. A prospective cash flow multiple of around six
times is not demanding for equities, especially since Italy's strong export
performance since the lira's exit from the ERM is starting to generate
healthy growth in industrial earnings.
Yesterday's weakness in both markets suggests that the political fog will
have to clear before these factors come to the fore. There are risks along
the way. Not least is the possibility that worries about fiscal policy might
cause the Bank of Italy to go slow on interest rate cuts. With the domestic
economy still weak, that would be particularly worrying for equities.
</TEXT>
