FT  30 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CBC1's new current affairs programme with shorter items, Here And Now (7.30)
reports on chocoholics, and what can be done to lighten the impact of next
week's tax increases.
What with the Question Time job going to a Dimbleby, and Jeremy Paxman,
according to scuttlebutt, holding out for too high a fee as questionmaster
on the about-to-be revived University Challenge, it seems that the search
for a role other than Newsnight presenter for Paxo continues. Today he
presents Elizabeth The Last: The Radical Option (8.10 BBC2). This is a pilot
for what could become an occasional series. Professor Stephen Haseler puts
the case for a British republic.
As part of Channel 4's French season Dispatches reports on a year in the
life of a tough school in Paris where teachers have to contend with
superglue in the keyholes and pupils armed with tear gas bombs (9.00).
Ironically French Letters (9.45) is one of those rare programmes not about
condoms. It offers a picture of the 'other' France: rundown housing estates
and illegal immigrants.
