<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Ice-cream clash with EU looms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading UK ice-cream manufacturers were yesterday cleared of
anti-competitive distribution practices by the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission. The decision, however, is set to spark a clash with Europe over
competition policy.
A nine-month inquiry found that 'freezer exclusivity' - providing free
freezer cabinets to shops on condition they are not used to stock ice-cream
from other suppliers - did not operate against the public interest.
The commission found no evidence of excessive prices or profits being made
in the sale of ice-cream for immediate consumption - so-called 'impulse
ice-cream'. It said recent market trends suggested competition had been
effective irrespective of any exclusivity.
But its conclusion that the tied offer of freezers to retailers was not a
barrier to market entry could bring the UK into conflict with Brussels.
The European Commission is also investigating the issue of freezer
exclusivity after a complaint from Mars, the US confectionery group, which
entered the impulse ice-cream business in 1989.
Brussels has yet to rule on the issue but an indication of its thinking came
recently when it vetted the takeover by Unilever, the UK-Dutch consumer
goods group, of Ortiz-Miko, France's third-biggest ice-cream producer. The
European Commission said freezer exclusivity was a serious barrier to market
entry.
Disagreement between London and Brussels over the issue could force the UK
authorities to back down, thereby throwing into doubt the practicality of
Brussels's attempts to encourage greater subsidiarity - the principle where
powers are devolved to the lowest practical level  - in competition policy.
The MMC report was welcomed by Unilever, whose subsidiary Birds Eye Walls
has two-thirds of the market for impulse purchases of wrapped ice-creams,
and more than half of the total UK impulse market, valued at Pounds 275m in
1992.
The company said it was 'a clear vindication of its practice of providing
free brand-linked freezer cabinets to its retail customers'. It has supplied
60,000 freezers to 42,000 shops in the UK.
Mr Simon Bullimore, managing director of Mars Confectionery, said the report
protected Wall's existing and profitable exclusive distribution
arrangements.
'Freezer exclusivity is clearly an anti-competitive practice which still
adversely affects competitors, wholesalers, retailers and consumers alike,'
he added.
The Consumers' Association was also critical. 'The MMC has once again failed
consumers with a muddle-headed and misguided report which puts the interests
of industry firmly in first place.'
The MMC found a simple monopoly existed in favour of Birds Eye Walls and a
complex monopoly in favour of BEW, Nestle, which bought Lyons Maid at the
end of 1992, and Mars. Together they accounted for 88 per cent of sales of
wrapped ice-creams for immediate consumption in 1992.
BEW and Nestle operate and enforce exclusivity where possible. Mars supplies
cabinets to retailers but only requires that a full range of its ice-creams
be stocked. The monopolies commission concluded this had the same effect as
exclusivity.
BEW and Nestle argued that freezer exclusivity had extended the market and
consumer choice to many small outlets which would not otherwise have stocked
ice-cream.
Mars had asked the MMC to ban exclusivity as anti-competitive. Since
entering the market in 1989 it has achieved a market share of 16 per cent
for wrapped ice-creams.
The MMC's conclusions were that exclusivity posed less of a problem than
when it last looked at the the market in 1979. Retailers could add a second
freezer, and this had happened in as much as 80 per cent of outlets. They
could terminate exclusive agreements at short notice and could purchase
their own freezer and buy ice-cream at lower prices.
It concluded: 'We are not convinced that consumer choice would be
significantly improved were exclusivity ended.'
Editorial comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
