<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Buy-out teams emerge in British Coal ahead of privatisation
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Several potential management buy-out teams are emerging within British Coal
as the corporation prepares to publish preliminary information next month
about the five areas on offer for privatisation.
None of the possible bids involves executive board members, although at
least one regional director, Mr Alan Houghton of the central north region
containing most of the Yorkshire pits, is believed to be interested in
leading a bid for the mines he manages.
According to Coal UK, the Financial Times newsletter, Mr Bob Siddall,
director of British Coal's opencast operations, is studying the possibility
of bidding for all deep-mine areas in England. Mr Jeff Ainley, manager of
the Hatfield pit near Doncaster, has also told British Coal of his interest
in leading a management buy-out of the pit.
Separate bids are thought to be under consideration by managers in Wales and
Scotland for the regions in which they operate.
British Coal would not comment yesterday on whether any managers had
notified the chairman of their interests.
Mr Tim Eggar, energy minister, told the Commons yesterday that the
corporation had given instructions to employees to ensure that no potential
purchasers were given preferential access to information before
privatisation.
</TEXT>
