<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Oftel plans renewed assault on BT's dominance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Don Cruickshank, the telecommunications regulator, plans a raft of fresh
measures aimed at encouraging competition for British Telecom.
Mr Cruickshank intends to make the UK's regulatory regime more accommodating
to companies planning new services, and to take a more active stance in
policing existing operators.
BT, which commands nearly 90 per cent of the UK telecoms market, is likely
to come under closer scrutiny by Oftel, the telecoms regulatory office
headed by Mr Cruickshank. But cable companies building combined television
and telephone networks in urban areas can also expect to have their
activities examined.
In a report on future policy, included in Oftel's 1993 annual report
published yesterday, Mr Cruickshank was sharply critical of the status quo.
'New entrants are not yet delivering the range of choice I am looking for,'
he said. 'We cannot relax merely because licences have been issued and
promises made . . . we still have a long, long way to go.'
He is impressed by the greater range of telecoms services in the US, and
Oftel will publish studies comparing the range and quality of services in
the UK with those of the US and France.
Areas highlighted for Oftel scrutiny in the next year include cable
companies' adherence to Oftel-agreed timetables for constructing networks.
The annual report shows a sharp fall in consumer complaints to Oftel, from
41,026 in 1992 to 23,413 last year.
Separately, BT and Mercury, its main competitor, have announced cuts of up
to 25 per cent in the price of international ISDN services, high-capacity
lines used by businesses for data transfer and video-conferencing.
The government signalled its concern yesterday at delays by US authorities
in allowing British operators to compete in the US.
Lord Strathclyde, a Department of Trade and Industry minister, told a
conference in London: 'In the US some interests seem to want to close off
their market to international competition rather than see International
Simple Resale (ISR) bring down tariffs.'
ISR would allow new competitors to use leased international lines to provide
a service connected to the public network in both the US and the UK. The US
is blocking ISR pending studies of the 'openness' of the UK market.
</TEXT>
