FT  30 MAR 94 / Ministers accused on Ulster committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour yesterday accused the government of engaging in 'gerrymandering at
its worst' by allotting representatives of Ulster's nationalist community
only one seat on the new 13-member Northern Ireland select committee. The
opposition, however, failed in its attempt to replace Tory nominees.
As MPs cleared the way for the new body to begin work soon after Easter, Mr
Kevin McNamara, the shadow Northern Ireland secretary, charged ministers
with misrepresenting Labour's parliamentary strength by giving it only two
seats.
Mr McNamara said ministers were setting up the committee in return for
support from the Ulster Unionist party's nine MPs in a 'squalid' deal to
shore up an 'increasingly shaky' government.
The formation of the committee - widely seen as a symbol of the government's
commitment to the province's unionist majority - 'reduces still further' the
prospects of agreement on a devolved Ulster assembly with a broad Irish
dimension, he said.
MPs from both leading unionist parties spoke in support of the committee but
Mr Eddie McGrady, the MP for South Down who is set to be the mainly Roman
Catholic Social Democratic and Labour party's sole representative, said his
party had not been consulted on it.
MPs rejected a series of Labour motions seeking to replace Tory nominees for
the committee with its own representatives. The original motion setting out
the names of the committee members was then approved without a vote.
In Belfast, loyalist terrorists yesterday launched a gun and rocket attack
on Sinn Fein offices and said they would continue to target Sinn Fein and
the IRA whether or not they accepted the Downing Street declaration.
No one was injured in the attack, for which the outlawed Ulster Freedom
Fighters admitted responsibility.
Sinn Fein later called on Dublin to join it in pressing for a public inquiry
into allegations of collusion between loyalist paramilitaries and agents of
the British government to attack nationalists.
</TEXT>
