<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Health pay put first in line for treatment: The new chief
executive of the NHS tells Alan Pike of his plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the first challenges for Mr Alan Langlands, who becomes chief
executive of the National Health Service on Friday, will be to put a
strategy for introducing local pay bargaining in place by early autumn.
Last month's reports from the pay review bodies for medical staff called for
the devolution of pay determination to local level. The review bodies and
the government see this as an inevitable consequence of the 1991 NHS
reforms, but most hospitals and health authorities have been slow to take up
the challenge of dismantling the service's centralised pay structures.
Mr Langlands said in an interview with the Financial Times that this year
the NHS management would have to give the review bodies a 'convincing
explanation' of what changes could be achieved in 1995. 'Our initial
evidence to the review bodies in the autumn will have to reflect very
significant progress.'
Transitional arrangements were likely to be proposed, rather than trying to
change the existing structure in a single leap, he said. He was also
concerned that local managers taking on the new responsibilities should
understand that human resource management involved more than just pay.
Attention must be given to wider terms and conditions, communications,
training and staffing structures.
'It is not just a case of sending a brief signal saying: do it. It is about
getting managers to understand the importance of harnessing the workforce
for the good of the organisation. This has got to be a two-way street.
Employees have got to get something out of it as well.'
Mr Langlands is, like Sir Duncan Nichol - his predecessor to whom he was
deputy - a career NHS manager. He takes over as chief executive exactly
three years after the government's health reforms restructured the service
around an internal market. Although Mr Langlands acknowledged that the
quality of NHS managers continued to vary, he said the reforms had liberated
them from much of the service's old hierarchy and increased opportunities
for effective management at local level.
One of his early tasks will be to issue new codes on corporate governance,
prepared in the wake of examples of serious mismanagement and abuse of
procedures in Wessex and West Midlands regional health authorities.
Drafts of the codes had, said Mr Langlands, produced positive comments from
the Audit Commission, the Institute of Chartered Accountants and Mr Robert
Sheldon, chairman of the Commons public accounts committee.
The Labour party published a health policy consultation document last month
which, while pledging to abolish the market principles of the government's
reforms, retained organisational separation between the purchasing of
healthcare and its provision. Mr Langlands believed this is one of a number
of examples of growing political consensus on health policy, which he
welcomed. One area where there is no consensus, however, is the GP
fund-holding scheme, which Labour and the British Medical Association say
has led to some family doctors gaining fast-track hospital treatment for
their patients.
Mr Langlands said that while he recognised the concerns of some doctors,
most criticisms of fundholding had related to single, anecdotal cases. He
believes the overall fairness of the scheme can be demonstrated.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
