<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Reuters raps information 'misers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Reuters, the news and financial information group, has revealed a lurking
threat to British business - the information miser.
Research commissioned by it showed that more than two-thirds of British
directors believe their bosses and colleagues play 'information politics' by
hoarding rather than sharing vital knowledge.
Disinterested observers who might suppose Reuters has an axe to grind would
be correct: the reporting of this new scourge coincided with the launch
yesterday of two new Reuters on-line business information products.
The survey of more than 500 British executives says one in three claims to
have had vital business information withheld from them - half of those
blaming the 'political' ambition of peers and seniors.
Nearly 90 per cent believed a free flow of information was vital to their
businesses. Two-thirds also believed they spent more time than they should
just searching for the right information - an average of two hours per week.
Ms Marion King, managing director of Reuters Business Information, said:
'Organisations need to have information policies - a formal method of
communicating information upwards, downwards and around the organisation.'
Reuters is marketing two information services - Business Briefing, which
offers subscribers direct access to either current or archive information,
and Business Alert, which automatically provides updates within pre-set
criteria. Industry research estimates the European market for on-line
information was worth Pounds 2bn last year and is projected to reach Pounds
4.77bn by 1997 - a compound annual growth rate of 24 per cent.
</TEXT>
