<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Pounds 9.4m aid to halt Jaguar move abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is to pay Pounds 9.4m in grant aid to Jaguar, the luxury car
subsidiary of Ford, to deter the US carmaker from moving the assembly of the
next generation Jaguar XJS sports car from the UK to Portugal.
The European Commission, which approved the aid yesterday, said that 883
jobs would be safeguarded at Jaguar by 1998 through the granting of regional
selective assistance. Jaguar will also receive up to Pounds 1.8m in
assistance in kind for training from the local authorities in Coventry and
Birmingham.
It is understood that Ford, which acquired Jaguar in late 1989, had closely
considered transferring the Pounds 187m sports car project to its plant at
Azambuja, close to Lisbon, where it assembles the Transit van.
The Portuguese authorities had bidded for the project with an attractive
rival aid package.
Jaguar is due to begin production of the car, code-named X100, in 1996. It
will replace the ageing XJS grand tourer coupe and convertible range, which
was launched in 1975.
The commission said that Jaguar planned to invest Pounds 187m in the X100
project during the four years from 1993 to 1997.
Jaguar intends to install a new low-cost, low-volume production facility in
its plant at Castle Bromwich, Birmingham, where the body for the new range
will be welded and painted.
The project will mark a new stage in the integration of Jaguar into the Ford
production network. The body panels for the X100 will be stamped at Ford's
plant at Halewood, Merseyside, while a new range of V8 engines, code-named
AJ26, will be produced at Ford's engine plant at Bridgend in south Wales.
Jaguar is investing about Pounds 100m in the new engine range, which will be
launched first in the X100.
The commission said yesterday: 'Given that the new project requires the
replacement of the old body and car assembly line of the XJS, the company
has actively examined various alternative locations for this project.'
It is understood that Ford also looked initially at possible locations in
the US, but the aid package made Portugal the main rival to continuing
assembly in the UK.
The grant will be paid in instalments from this year until 1997 and there is
a provision for withholding or clawing back aid if there is
'under-achievement' in safeguarding employment.
The first stage in the renewal of Jaguar's range will be reached this
summer, when it begins production of the new generation XJ6, code-named
X300, in which it is investing about Pounds 150m.
</TEXT>
