<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / City expresses doubts on golden handcuffs scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The City reacted with some scepticism yesterday to the decision by Smith New
Court, the securities house, to develop a staff bonus scheme with golden
handcuffs attached.
The firm wants to allocate a proportion of its annual bonuses to staff in
the form of its own shares. These would be held in trust and only handed
over three years later to those still working for the firm.
The personnel manager of one competitor said yesterday: 'Smith New Court is
taking a calculated risk. This may make it more difficult for them recruit
staff. It may also up the bids and add to labour costs. The only winners
will be the recruitment consultants.'
A headhunting firm said the scheme reflected increasing concern about
poaching of top employees. 'We are finding that forms of deferred
compensation are proving popular,' it said. 'Increasingly people are getting
paid a good proportion of their bonus in terms of shares.'
In the secretive world of City securities houses few are willing to comment
publicly on remuneration which is often high and sometimes structured to
avoid tax payments.
However, a number of securities houses have introduced some element of
compensation designed to generate staff loyalty, including deferred cash
bonuses and share options. Most differentiate between current-year bonuses
and long-term share option plans designed to boost loyalty.
The Smith New Court proposals stand out because they: link the two elements;
use existing shares rather than new equity; involve a high proportion of
total equity - up to 15 per cent; and will be used with a relatively large
number of employees - perhaps 15 per cent of the total.
The concept is less surprising to US firms, which were largely de-regulated
in the early 1970s. Merrill Lynch pays some senior staff a proportion of
bonus in shares. Lehman Brothers is believed to offer staff compensation
deferred over three years.
Salomon Brothers, the securities arm of Salomon, has been paying some staff
a proportion of their bonuses in shares for about three years so that 19 per
cent of equity is now held by staff. Shares are held in trust for five years
during which time they cannot be traded. Thereafter they are redeemable
whether or not the employee has left the company.
Some firms, such as Goldman Sachs, have been able to retain staff loyalty
because bonuses are paid in the form of equity stakes that cannot be cashed
without considerable difficulty.
In the UK, some argue that high staff turnover and low loyalty began with
de-regulation of the City's financial institutions in 1986. Until then,
brokers were traditionally privately held partnerships whose staff held
shares. As the organisations obtained stock market quotations, this loyalty
through ownership was lost.
Ironically, the firms said still to be among the most profitable are those
which retained the more traditional ownership structure with their shares
held privately, including Cazenove, based in the UK, and Goldman Sachs.
Recruitment, Page 12
</TEXT>
