<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / CBI pulls out of talks on works councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Confederation of British Industry yesterday withdrew from discussions on
the ground rules for establishing works councils in European multi-nationals
as Unice, the European employers' body, went further than the British
employers' group was prepared to accept.
The CBI's decision to withdraw, after pressure from members and other UK
employers' groups, will not prevent talks continuing - at least until
tomorrow - between Unice and the European Trades Union Congress.
But it raises questions about the viability of the social dialogue between
Unice and the ETUC, which the European Commission is keen to promote as an
alternative to producing detailed directives. CBI officials say the social
dialogue as now structured does not allow national employers' organisations
to consult their members properly.
On works councils, the CBI objected to the accepted Unice principle that
there should be minimum requirements if voluntary agreement at company level
is not possible, and also that information and consultation should be a
legally enforceable right.
The government's opt-out from some aspects of the social chapter means UK
employers will only be affected by works council legislation through their
continental European businesses.
The commission has agreed to pass a directive on works councils if Unice and
the ETUC fail to reach agreement. That means the ETUC has little incentive
to agree to anything less than what is laid out in the directive.
Ninety-one per cent of foreign-owned companies would not change their
attitude to the UK if the government reduced its commitment to the European
Union, a survey has found.
The size of the UK market is the main attraction for foreign investors,
according to a survey of 800 executives of foreign-owned companies,
conducted for the accountants and management consultants KPMG Peat Marwick.
Only 3 per cent of foreign companies cited cheap labour as an investment
reason.
Foreign-owned Companies in the UK. KPMG, 8 Salisbury Square, London EC4Y
8BB.
