<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Tension rises as US rebuffs Japan trade package offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Trade tension between the US and Japan worsened last night as Washington
rebuffed a Japanese market-opening package, dismissing it as 'of little
substance'.
Mr Mickey Kantor, the US trade representative, said that the package
unveiled earlier in the day by Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, the Japanese prime
minister, was a 'half-finished work' that did not meet US concerns.
Mr Hosokawa had hoped the package would go a long way to meeting US pressure
for steps to stimulate Japan's economy and open its markets wider to foreign
goods, reducing its trade surplus. Mr Kantor's rejection, backed by the
White House, will be a severe blow to Mr Hosokawa.
The package was carefully put together after the US laid the groundwork for
possible trade sanctions in the wake of Japan's refusal last month to
provide numerical targets for imports.
Japanese officials claimed yesterday that except for setting numerical
targets, their package conceded most demands made in previous negotiations
with the US. The package aims to boost the economy and open markets to
foreign goods through deregulation and enhanced competition, laying
particular stress on four sectors - telecommunications, medical equipment,
insurance and motor vehicle parts.
But Mr Kantor still insisted on 'qualitative and quantitative indicators' to
measure the progress of export penetration of Japan's markets. He indicated
he wanted specific agreements on key sectors, more movement in regulatory
reform and 'a significant new commitment toward macroeconomic stimulus'.
Mr Kantor said the package was not enough to lead to a resumption of the
US-Japanese trade talks that broke up without agreement during a summit in
Washington last month.
But he sought to soften the US rejection by referring to the measures as 'a
work in progress'. The US was not discouraged, he said, adding: 'Our door
remains open.'
Senator Max Baucus, chairman of the Senate international trade subcommittee,
could summon no more enthusiasm than Mr Kantor. 'This very modest package of
reforms that Japan unveiled yesterday only provides further evidence that
Japan only makes real concessions under concrete pressure,' he said.
Mr Kantor said the package showed progress in the area of government
procurement, but there was 'no movement' in the motor vehicle and insurance
sectors. 'We don't want cosmetic agreements,' he added.
Yesterday the dollar dropped sharply in New York to Y103.6 against Y104.62
previously on speculation that the US would push for a higher yen. In Tokyo
this morning it opened at Y103.2.
Package details, Page 6
