<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 94 / Norwich Union suspends pensions direct sales force
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Norwich Union, one of the UK's leading insurers, yesterday suspended 800
agents - including its entire life and pensions direct sales force - for a
month after the industry's regulator identified breakdowns in management
control.
The move means that from midnight last night no one in the company's direct
sales force will be able to give financial advice to a customer until he or
she has successfully completed a re-training programme.
Lautro, the life industry's self-regulatory organisation, prompted the
suspensions after it uncovered shortcomings in the way Norwich Union was
implementing higher training and competency standards which took effect in
April 1993. This is the first time a financial regulator has taken such a
drastic step against a large company.
Possible disciplinary action, including fines, against the company is a
separate matter for consideration by Lautro.
Mr Philip Scott, Norwich Union life and pensions general manager, said he
did not believe any customers had been placed at a disadvantage, since the
company operated a quality control programme separate from the process of
selling, to ensure that appropriate products were sold. Some 600 of the
agents suspended are in Norwich Union's direct sales force, and the
remaining 200 work for companies which are the life insurer's appointed
representatives.
Norwich Union's sales force is paid entirely on commission but Mr Scott
insisted that the system of payment was 'largely irrelevant' to selling
practices.
The direct sales force accounts for about 10 per cent of Norwich Union's new
life and pensions business. Mr Scott said that the company's loss from the
month when they would not be selling would be 'relatively small'.
Mr Allan Bridgewater, group chief executive, emphasised that the suspension
did not affect Norwich Union's business through independent financial
advisers and Leeds Permanent Building Society.
Lautro's action comes after it warned it would take a tough line with
companies which failed to meet its standards.
Mr Scott said the weaknesses found by Lautro in October had already been
picked up in an internal review. Some 320 sales agents had already left
since the review began last summer, he said. Seventeen managers, including
the national sales manager for direct business, have also left.
Lex, Page 22
Results, Page 25
</TEXT>
