<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Holliday pays Pounds 52m for Reckitt's Blue division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Holliday Chemical, the industrial dyes company which went public last year,
is buying one of Britain's oldest chemicals businesses from Reckitt &amp;
Colman, the consumer products group.
Holliday is paying Pounds 52m for Reckitt Colours International which has
been making synthetic ultramarine for use in clothes laundering since 1883.
Based in Hull, where Isaac Reckitt first started making washing blue in the
1850s, RCI now supplies mainly industrial markets, particularly for use in
colouring plastics.
Reckitt &amp; Colman said the disposal was in line with its strategy of
concentrating on consumer goods. Most of RCI's 'laundry grade' product goes
to a separate Reckitt division which will continue to sell laundry blue
under the Reckitt's Blue and Robin Blue brands.
The latter is a leading brand in India. Demand has dried up in the developed
world because of the introduction of other whiteners in washing powders.
Holliday is funding the acquisition largely by a one-for-four rights issue
at 180p, raising a net Pounds 36m. Mr Michael Peagram, chairman, said he
first approached Reckitt about the business four years ago and a deal was
nearly agreed last November. But Holliday was forced to pull out after its
shares slumped following a profit warning.
The shares have since recovered allowing the deal to proceed. 'I would have
been very peeved if we had missed it,' said Mr Peagram.
The original plan for a rights issue of convertible preference shares was
scrapped last week as market yields rose. But Mr Peagram stressed that the
deal would still enhance Holliday's earnings per share.
RCI made a Pounds 6.2m pre-tax on sales of Pounds 29.4m last year and
Holliday is paying only 12.5 times historic earnings. Its shares fell 9p to
201p.
After the write-off of goodwill Holliday's pro forma gearing will rise to 65
per cent but Mr Peagram said it could still afford to make another Pounds
20m acquisition without issuing more shares. He ruled out a further rights
issue before the end of this year.
</TEXT>
