<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / OFT attacks copier industry over selling 'malpractices'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Unscrupulous selling practices in the UK photocopier industry were condemned
yesterday by the Office of Fair Trading after a 17-month investigation.
Sir Bryan Carsberg, director-general of fair trading, said the investigation
had 'revealed an extraordinary variety of malpractices and excesses'. But he
has decided against immediate legislation to clean up the industry, calling
instead for greater transparency in photocopier contracts.
Business was partly to blame for allowing malpractices to flourish by
failing to shop around or recognise the importance of photocopier contracts,
he said.
The industry had made progress through trade associations towards reducing
unacceptable selling practices and deserved the opportunity to show
self-regulation could work. He warned that if progress was not maintained he
would use his powers to revoke consumer credit licences and could refer the
supply of photocopiers to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The decision to give self-regulation a chance was welcomed by the Finance &amp;
Leasing Association and the Photocopier Suppliers Association, both of which
have produced guidelines. The Campaign to Clean Up Copier Contracts
criticised the OFT report for its 'lack of sanctions in dealing with clearly
identified problems'.
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer spokesman, said he would table a
Commons motion calling for legislation to compensate the thousands who had
been duped by unscrupulous photocopier and leasing companies.
The most common problems identified by the OFT were: contract periods much
longer than the lives of equipment; obscure and steep escalations of service
charges; and costly settlement terms - not disclosed in advance - when a
business wanted to end a contract early.
Sir Bryan said lease and service-inclusive, cost-per-copy, contracts with an
obligation to pay for a minimum volume of usage, had caused particular
problems. Some customers found themselves facing unavoidable escalating
service charges.
The director-general said he would carry out a further review early next
year. In the meantime he wanted to see a number of improvements in
practices.
Settlements should reflect only losses suffered by the leasing company or
dealer from early termination of the contract. Trade associations should
also discourage lease and service-inclusive cost-per-copy contracts.
Tighter control urged, Page 12
Editorial Comment, Page 21
</TEXT>
