FT  29 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today's semi-final in the Young Musician Of The Year competition is for
string players (6.55 BBC2).
You could switch to Channel 4 at 9.00 and stay for four and a half hours.
Without Walls begins with a report on Britain's cultural heritage as seen by
Europeans who live here 'but whose affection for England and the English
doesn't stop them from taking a clear-eyed look at our strengths and
weaknesses'. Given our supposed inadequacies in cuisine, dress sense, and
sex, it will be interesting to see what strengths we are allowed. The second
half (9.30) sustains the European theme: Isambard Kingdom Brunel returns
from the dead to inspect the Channel Tunnel.
That is followed by Betty Blue, a 1986 French movie about love and
obsession, noted for its sexual explicitness. This version is the director's
cut which means three hours instead of two. The longer version is said to be
slower and less amusing (10.00).
In Omnibus the admirable Patricia Routledge plays Sister Hildegard, a 12th
century nun, scientist, painter, and composer (10.25 BBC1).
