<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Gatwick Express makes surprise early profit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gatwick Express, the first British Rail service set for privatisation,
carried more passengers than planned and made an unexpected profit in its
first few months as an independent business.
Mr Robert Mason, managing director, said the company, which runs non-stop
trains between Gatwick Airport and London Victoria, had expected to break
even, but better-than-expected passenger numbers boosted ticket revenues by
Pounds 2m.
Ticket revenues rose to Pounds 27m in the past 12 months with Gatwick
Express operating as an independent 'shadow franchise' in the last six. The
company had budgeted for ticket revenues of Pounds 25m.
The management team plans to renew its entire train fleet at a cost of about
Pounds 45m if it is successful in staging a buy-out.
Gatwick Express's present locomotives are 28 years old and its coaches are
19 years old. It operates seven trains providing 134 daily services, but
plans to buy eight sets of locomotives and coaches to allow for maintenance.
Mr Mason said the company was 'very happy' with its Pounds 8m contract with
Railtrack, the state-owned company set up to run BR's track and signalling
after privatisation. This guarantees access to the track between Gatwick and
London and to two reserved platforms at Gatwick. Managers in other British
Rail divisions have complained that Railtrack's track charges are too high.
Gatwick Express's one concern is that Railtrack should not allow Victoria
station to be turned into a shopping mall, so marginalising train
operations.
Gatwick Express has acquired the lease to run Gatwick Airport station. As
station operator it must treat all train companies using the station
equally. This means it will reduce promotional advertising for its services
at Gatwick and create a single ticket office for its own services and those
of its two rivals, Network SouthEast and Thameslink.
Gatwick Express plans improvements to its services to attract more
passengers, including a coach service from Victoria for travellers staying
in London hotels and an improved setting-down area for travellers arriving
by car.
It has also been marketing its service to the airlines serving Gatwick and
to tour operators. It wants airlines to sell train tickets on aircraft and
tour operators to include a train ticket in package holidays.
</TEXT>
