<DATE>940329
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Race bias complaints against police rise
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Allegations of racial discrimination and serious assault against police
officers rose sharply last year, but the total of complaints of all kinds
fell, the Police Complaints Authority said yesterday.
The authority considered 17,991 complaints last year, a fall of 7 per cent
on the previous year. It allowed 17 per cent more complaints to be dropped
by police forces than in 1992 - 7,075 compared with 6,035. These included
allegations lodged for malicious or tactical reasons or where the
complainant chose not to co-operate with the inquiry.
The remaining 10,916 investigated complaints was 18 per cent down on 1992.
Complaints alleging corruption arose from 12 in 1992 to 17 last year.
The authority agreed to supervise 951 cases, up a quarter on 1992 and the
highest such total ever. That was thanks largely to the number of
allegations involving serious injury or death, which are required to be
supervised. Overall, forces referred 4,139 cases for possible supervision, 7
per cent down on 1992.
The number of complaints of racial discrimination rose from 67 in 1992 to
291. Disciplinary action was taken on 4 per cent of those complaints,
compared with 10 per cent of all investigated complaints.
Sir Leonard Peach, chairman of the complaints authority, said: 'This
substantial rise is due in part to more accurate recording and a greater
awareness of the complaints system, but there may be a greater unwillingness
to accept racially offensive behaviour.'
It was difficult, however, to substantiate the complaints to the required
level of proof - beyond reasonable doubt. 'Officers are unlikely to use
offensive language within the hearing of independent witnesses,' he said.
'It is frequently difficult to prove a complainant was specifically targeted
because of his or her ethnic origin.'
</TEXT>
