<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Councils bid for Careers Service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Partnerships between local education authorities and Training and Enterprise
Councils form the bulk of the 13 pathfinders for the new-look Careers
Service.
The new organisations have been formed in 13 English regions to take over
the running of the service from local authorities.
The outlets, launched by the Department of Employment yesterday, promise
'greater innovation' in helping to find young people a job. Bids to run
services in other regions will be invited in May.
The government hoped when it invited competitive bids for the service that
private-sector training organisations might bid. However, in all but one
case the pathfinder services will be a partnership between Tecs, which
administer government-funded training programmes in England and Wales, and
local authorities. The service in Bedfordshire is the only one not formally
to involve its local Tec.
Miss Ann Widdecombe, employment minister, denied yesterday that the new
organisations were a 'repackaging' of the previous service.
</TEXT>
