<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Binder partner sceptical of merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The managing partner of the Scottish arm of BDO Binder Hamlyn, the UK's
eighth-largest accountancy firm, yesterday expressed scepticism over the
possibility of merging with Arthur Andersen, the fourth-largest.
Mr Ian Valentine said: 'The whole deal has got to be very carefully looked
at. I can see difficulties in the size, culture and nature of the regional
offices.'
His views reflected concerns expressed by several partners in the 11
regional practices that comprise Binder and which could jeopardise a merger
of the entire firm.
The comments came after it emerged over the weekend that Mr Jim Wadia,
managing partner for Arthur Andersen, wrote to Binder's senior partner two
weeks ago proposing a merger. The regional heads of the firm met last night
to learn fuller details of the proposals.
It also emerged yesterday that both the single Binder firm covering London
and Leeds, and the separate partnership for Manchester, were involved in the
discussions with Andersen. These two practices represent the bulk of the
firm's income and clients.
Senior partners within these two Binder's practices are believed to be keen
to press ahead with a merger.
Andersen is believed to be willing to accept even if none of the other
practices want to proceed. Full details of the merger are still subject to
discussion. However, it is unlikely that the deal would involve any payment.
Most discussion will concentrate on the terms on which partners in Binder
would be allocated 'units' or shares within the Andersen partnership.
Partners at Binder are now examining their deeds in detail to understand the
nature of the voting that would be necessary to approve any merger.
</TEXT>
