<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Manager aims to kick a deal into touch: Peter Marsh meets a
customer who feels the OFT does not go far enough on photocopier leasing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Frank Wright, purchasing manager of the Rugby Football Union, spent
yesterday trying to kick into touch a photocopier leasing deal which will
cost Pounds 68,000 over the next five years unless he cancels the agreement
at the cost of Pounds 23,000.
Mr Wright criticised yesterday's report by the Office of Fair Trading for
not going far enough to regulate the photocopier supply industry, in spite
of its criticisms of malpractices in offering contracts.
Four years ago the union - which regulates the affairs of about 3,000 rugby
clubs in England and is based in Twickenham, west London - signed an
agreement with Southern Business Group, a big photocopier supplier, to lease
a machine over nine years.
Mr Wright said the original agreement would have meant the union paying
Pounds 198,000 over nine years, with a penalty payment of Pounds 60,000 for
opting out.
Southern has since agreed to modify the terms, involving a 30 per cent cut
in the monthly leasing charge. Mr Wright still feels aggrieved about the
amount the union is paying.
He said the original contract, agreed before he joined the union, was signed
by another officer 'without a great deal of thought'.
The agreement, based on the union paying 2.5p per month for every paper
copied, with leasing charges on top, seemed good at the time. But, Mr Wright
said, the union had not fully worked out how much it would cost over the
time of the contract.
'Once we signed up, we were hooked,' he said.
Mr Wright would have liked the OFT paper to go further in forcing the
industry to be more open about the costs of contracts, with greater
protection for consumers who feel they get a raw deal.
Mr David McErlain, chairman of Southern, said: 'The union's legal position
is hopeless, but we have listened constructively to what Mr Wright has to
say.
'We want to maintain a commercial relationship with the bloke. We are now
down to honest-to-goodness bartering, proving that we can be flexible.'
He said that many of the high leasing charges in the industry in the early
1990s stemmed from the high interest rates at that time. As borrowing costs
had come down, the industry had been able to pass on these reductions to
customers.
The fall in interest rates had been reflected in Southern's offer to reduce
the cost to the union of opting out of the supply contract from Pounds
60,000 to Pounds 28,000.
As to the 'malpractices and excesses' which the OFT had identified in some
sections of the industry, he conceded that 'some companies have been slow to
react to criticism'. In Southern's case, however, the company was always
willing to listen to its customers.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
PRINTING MONEY: HOW THE COSTS OF LEASING PHOTOCOPIERS STACK UP
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
