<HEADLINE>
FT  29 MAR 94 / Delors guarantee may sway sceptics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers were preparing last night for a tough fight to sell the European
Union enlargement compromise to sceptical Conservative backbenchers.
The key is likely to be a written guarantee from Mr Jacques Delors,
president of the European Commission, of British independence in social and
employment matters.
The assurance, which the government hopes to receive this morning, would
signal an end to EU attempts to use health-and-safety legislation to
circumvent Britain's opt-out from the social chapter of the Maastricht
treaty.
The assurance is intended to address widespread fears among Conservative
backbenchers that the EU is determined to roll back de-regulatory reforms
introduced by the Conservatives since 1979.
The most recent example occurred two weeks ago, when the government was
forced to announce a Pounds 65m increase in maternity payments because of a
European directive.
Other examples include:
A European parliament vote to force Britain to limit working hours for young
people such as paper boys and girls. The government wants the vote
overturned, if necessary by the European Court.
A House of Lords ruling that the 1978 Employment Protection Act is unlawful
because it fails to comply with EU legislation on the rights of part-time
workers.
Other social and employment policy initiatives emerging from Brussels are
equally at odds with the liberalising instincts of the British government.
These include proposals for compulsory works councils, which would give
unions a voice in running British companies.
Mr Padraig Flynn, the EU social affairs commissioner, is preparing a green
paper on job creation which is expected to culminate in a social action plan
to help halve the EU's level of unemployment to 9m workers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
